    </div>
    <div class="col-md-2-5ths case-image">
      <strong>Data Translation</strong><br>
      I began to experiment the different ways I could show all four datapoints: (1) calories gained, (2) calories lost, (3) time spent, and (4) Foursquare rating for each one I visited.<br><br>
      <strong>Visual Encoding</strong><br>
      <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-pizza/graph.JPG") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="Translated datapoints into a visualization"></div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
  </div><br>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-2-5ths case-image">
      Having plotted time on the y-axis and the pizzeria on the x-axis, I began thinking about what a single cell represented. Looking at the data, I noticed how the calorie counts would fit into multiples of 50. This "unit" of 50 though was not an intuitive increment for time. Chunking time into 50-minute blocks– 3-3:50pm, 3:50-4:20pm, etc could be confusing!<br><br>
      I eventually used 10-minute blocks for both the calorie count and time for consistency.<br><br>
      <strong>Making meaning of relationships</strong><br><br>
      Another challenge I faced stacking these blocks up a limited amount of space was that calories gained (shaded pink) consistently consumed more space than calories lost (shaded blue). This meant possibly risking legibility for the sake of visual consistency. (See how the first blue column stands just right to the left of the calories gained at the next stop.) <br><br>
      It was only when I had reconsidered the intrinsic relationship of gain and loss that I came up with the solution– to have the blue cells go on top of/ override the ones shaded in pink so that the remaining pink ones represented the net calories.<br><br>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths case-image">
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-5ths">
    </div>
